The offices include a kindergarten, the architects understood
The Avriopoint office building in Brno is the new headquarters of Arch.Design.
No one would have expected that he was also hiding a mini-school with everything in it - with colorful walls, imaginative furniture, a bunch of toys, and even a miniature playground on the outdoor terrace.
Since October last year, children of employees of Arch.Design can visit her.
The design-architectonic company Arch.Design, whose studios produced a number of important buildings in Brno, counted on the space for its company mini-school since the first drawings of the building Avriopoint.
She employs almost 90 people, mostly in the age of babyboom, and she cared so that the women of the designer and architect can quickly return to work.
Along with the possibility of shorter periods, the kindergarten benefit is offered by Arch.Design to its employees under the social programme.
The builders and architects thus have the opportunity to combine demanding jobs with child care.
The minischool was invented by the employees of Arch.Designu themselves and with the support of the management they managed to obtain a subsidy from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The company minischool is funded by the European Social Fund through the Operational Programme Human Resources and Employment and the State Budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to grant funding (a subsidy of CZK 2, 8 million), they were able to purchase equipment and equipment and provide qualified staff and operation for two years.
After exhaustion of the financial subsidy (2 years), Arch.Design is obliged for 3 years to operate a mini-school at its own expense.
The preparation of the project lasted one year and the application for a subsidy was significantly assisted by Economy Rating.
The care is provided by qualified staff, the day-to-day care is provided by a nurse and a teacher of the Ministry of Education, so children can go to kindergarten without age restrictions, yet most of them are over 3 years old.
Since it is a "minischool," only 5 children can be present at the same time, but more will be replaced during the day.
Kindergarten operations are flexible according to the needs of parents and children of all employees have the same right to use the kindergarten regardless of the company hierarchy.
Although it is individual education and care, the programme content in a mini-school is comparable to the framework programme for pre-school education.
Children not only play here, but they are also provided with quality teaching - from basic knowledge to preparation to school benches, English language is also taught.
The class is equipped not only with toys, stimulating games, but also with a computer that children can use.
The presence of small children directly in the company creates a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can check on their child at any time, and stress situations with delayed picking up children from kindergartens away from parents' workplaces fall away.
Parents thus use working hours more productively.
It is no wonder that there is naturally a loyal relationship between an employee and an employer.
Arch.Design has thus joined Czech companies, which offer significant benefits in recruiting new employees, are friendly to the family and through this program boosted personnel marketing.
The house of the bones fascinates even after 100 years.
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the staircase resembles the spine of a dinosaur, and the balconies are an open fish mouth.
This is the house of Casa Batlló in Barcelona by Catalan architect Antoni Gaudí.
Thanks to its organic shapes, the locals have earned the name House of Bones.
Organic shapes, wild colors, unusual use of stones, fragments of tiles and mosaics, a facade resembling scales and ubiquitous soft curves, all typical of the Art Nouveau Antoni Gaudí.
The facade of the house plays out dream lines, tender colors and textures resembling nature and animals.
In detailed observations, geometry, rhythm and a precise order can be seen.
At night, the whole facade of houses sounds even more dramatic; it is illuminated so that the impression of the color shine is enhanced.
The winding and twisting of shapes appears equally in interiors.
The wood in the waves is copied by window frames, railings, decorative elements of doors, peepholes and rails.
The House of Batlló, which is located in the Eixample district on the busy shopping street Passeig de Grácia No. 43, was built by architect Emilio Sal Cortes in 1877.
The reconstruction took place for two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, rich industrialist Josep Batlló, originally insisted on tearing down the old building and building a whole new one, soon accepted Gaudí's idea of an unusual and cheaper reconstruction.
Casa Batlló's Apartment House was not designed by Antoni Gaudí himself.
The architect Josep Maria Jujol worked with him.
It was on his design board that decorations were created for the representative apartment of the owner of the property and the use of mosaic on the facade.
A number of other artists and artists worked on the facade.
The joint work on Casa Batlló's designs started with successful cooperation between Jujola and Gaudí.
Jujol participated in the construction of Gaudí's house Casa Milá and Park Güell, in which there are other works of Gaudí.
From the locals soon to completion, he earned the name "Bone House" thanks to his organic shapes.
Others began calling him "shouting house " because of a specific window opening mechanism.
It is also said that the sword of St. George, the patron of Catalonia, is likened at the top of the building.
Other sculptural elements of the building also contain hidden religious motives.
Gaudí designed a unique central heating system with ventilation vents and typical chimneys for his time.
The bizarre may seem to be their forty-five-degree slope.
Gaudí had absolutely no respect for the construction regulations at the time and was not bound by them.
At the beginning of the construction, he obtained a building permit from the city, but the details of the planned reconstruction were so vague that two years later the city council was disfigured and asked for correction.
For example, the construction affected the fact that the building interfered with the pillar and the public sidewalk.
There has never been a correction, on the contrary: only 15 days after the call of the city district, Josep Batlló has applied (and successfully obtained) permission to rent the two highest floors of the building.
The owner himself moved to the lower floors.
In the gallery on the second floor there was a social salon and on the third floor of the bedroom and private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented by a jewelry store.
The whole six-story house intersects the stairwells, which can be climbed to the rooftop terrace itself.
The essential elements of the reconstruction were the abolition of all right angles and straight lines and their replacement with curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with the modern concept of connecting space.
The social part can be completely connected by opening a salon door and a larger company can communicate comfortably without maintaining the privacy needed for more intimate conversations.
Apart from the new facade, the house with Gaudi's reconstruction also received an unconventional roofing and two floors.
Gaudí's game with light, blue and white glazed tiles is impressive, surrounded by inner courtyards and skylights.
The game of two colors gives the maximum light on all floors of the house.
It was enough simply to bet on the principle that white reflects light more than dark, which, on the contrary, absorbs sunlight.
The House of Casa Batlló, which was included in the Unesco World Heritage Fund in 2005, can be visited by everyone.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and lavish apartment made available to the public.
The owners decided not to take this step until 2002, on the occasion of the celebration of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
They persisted in the tours as they found that it was a very advantageous business and additionally extended the tours with common and attic spaces, including roof terraces.
The entrance fee is definitely not negligible, it is EUR 16.50 and students, pensioners, groups and holders of tourist cards have a 20% discount.
The sum greatly exceeds the price of admission to other Gaudí buildings in the city.
If you want to taste the true atmosphere of the house with dragon towers, you must quickly make friends with one of the residents of the apartment building and visit it directly at home.
