People's surveillance devices want more and more parents, so they want to babysit their children.
Fearing for your own child brings more and more people to the idea of a GPS babysitter.
The system originally created for car search can also monitor people's movement, and thus help in such cases as the disappearance of nine-year-old Anika Janatková.
The device is about the size of a matchbox so far, but soon it can only be as big as a watch.
A lot of people got scared of the missing Anka case and started looking for means to protect their children better.
Even at the cost of violating their privacy.
"We are trying to tell everyone that this is not about spying, but about another means of reducing the likelihood of a tragedy happening," says Petr Pilin of Macro Weil, one of the suppliers of surveillance devices on the Czech market.
"I admit that in a case such devices may be abused, for example, if they are put in a bag by someone who doesn't know about it, but we haven't met such a case yet."
"Most customers actually buy it for security reasons," said Pilin.
According to him, the child should always know what purpose the "box " serves and how it is used in an emergency.
Child psychologist Dana Bočková points out that if the child doesn't want to wear anything like this, he'll just get rid of it.
"Even very young children show great creativity in how to deliberately lose some things when they don't want to be in control."
"Great expectations were called by the parents' cell phones, which can be turned off as well as these tracking devices," says Bočková.
According to her, it is also questionable whether such an establishment would actually help in the event of an attack.
"As far as the kidnapping is concerned, the perpetrator practically always ensures that the child has no electronics that could reveal his location."
"Now it's a phone."
"When the tracking devices begin to expand, they will look for them, because their sale will certainly be supported by massive advertising."
"In that case, criminals will always be one step ahead of the police," says the psychologist.
However, he admits that a similar device can help in the event of sudden assault by a pedophile.
According to Robert Čech from RC Monitoring, which offers tracking services for both cars and persons, even if the attack results in the immediate destruction of the tracking device, its presence can help.
"The device can be set to periodically send the position after a certain period of time."
"If damage occurs, at least the last position of the person concerned shall be available.'
"Even if one slips and remains stationary, the device will immediately send a warning with position," says Bohemia.
According to him, smart cell phones with navigation can also carry a similar service, where special software can be uploaded.
The problem with current surveillance units is that they are either instruments similar to matchbox pendants or smaller mobile phones.
They're always at risk of losing them.
According to Pilino of Macro Weil, this is why the device that looks like a normal digital watch is now being tested.
"This will have the greatest advantage in the fact that a possible aggressor does not have to recognize the tracking device at all."
"Or he will recognize them after some time and it can give the police extra time," he adds.
Whether the tracking device evolves into bracelets or pendants, they will still use the same technology that is used to babysit cars.
It is a combination of GPS location detection (which uses common autonavigation) and mobile phone functions that report the current position of the car.
