Longer index finger than ring finger indicates lower risk of cancer
Men who have a index finger longer than a ring finger are less at risk of developing prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a study published by the British Cancer Magazine on Wednesday.
It could be related to male testosterone hormone levels.
"Our results show that the relative length of the finger can serve as a simple test of the risk of prostate cancer, especially for men under the age of 60," said Ros Eeles, Professor of the Institute for Cancer Research at the University of Warwick.
The finger could thus help determine which men should be tested for prostate cancer, especially in combination with genetic risk or other factors such as family health burden, supplied by Eeles.
During the period 1994-2009, more than 1500 prostate cancer patients were followed by over 3,000 healthy men with colleagues in Britain.
More than half of the study participants had the index finger on their right hand shorter than the ring finger.
They had the same probability of prostate cancer as 19 percent of those whose fingers were as long.
However, in the case of those with a index finger longer than the ring finger, this risk fell by 33 percent, with a decrease of even 87 percent for men to 60.
The ratio of the length of the two fingers - formed in the prenatal period - appears to reflect the different levels of sex hormones exposed to the child in the uterus.
Less testosterone is consistent with a longer index finger.
Early research has shown that testosterone supports growing prostate cancer.
The leading Czech geneticist and former chairman of the Academy of Sciences, Professor Václav Pačes, told the Czech News Agency that he knew about this study very quickly, but it does not seem to him that the relationship between finger length and cancer was "completely proven".
