The promotion of democracy in Latin America is growing, as is the promotion of private enterprise.
Criminal activity raises more concern than unemployment.
And Brazil considers many regions to be more influential than the United States.
These are some of the results of the current survey of the Latin-barometro, which took place in 18 countries and was published exclusively in The Economist magazine.
Since the survey has been held regularly since 1995, it can monitor changes in attitudes across the whole area.
In this year's survey, which took place in September and early October, two related things dominate.
The first is that Latin America is in quite a happy mood.
The second is to increase the stability of attitudes towards democracy and its key institutions.
Support for democracy in several countries on the outskirts of the Pacific in South America has increased significantly (see Table 1).
For example, in Peru, where economic growth has been on average 6% per year since 2002, the promotion of democracy has increased from a minimum of 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
It also grew in Mexico, where economics recovered after a deep decline in production last year.
But only about half of the respondents in Mexico and Brazil, two of the most populous areas, are the democratic beliefs, which are tightening the regional average (see Chart 2).
About 44% of respondents across the region expressed satisfaction with how democracy works in practice in their country, it is the same number as last year, but compared to 2001, when it was 25%, it is a big increase (graph 3).
Some 34% said they trusted the House in their country and 45% trusted the government, again the same figures as last year, but this is a big difference compared to 2003 (17% and 24%).
Ten years ago, the economic crisis undermined democracy in Latin America.
Support was probably created during the global financial crisis because many Latin American countries suffered only a short recession and enjoyed a strong recovery.
In addition, a stronger social security network has helped protect poor people.
(The United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America announced this week that the ratio of Latin Americans living in poverty increased only slightly in 2009 and fell again to 32% this year.)
But the mood is changing in a wide range from ground to ground (see Chart 4).
Brazil's strong economic performance and its outgoing President Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva's popularity are reflected in a widely accepted sense of progress.
This situation is more rare in Mexico and Central America, where the recession was more serious and the state of violent crime deteriorated.
Only the second time more respondents across Latin America have seen crime as the most important problem rather than unemployment (see Chart 5).
Some 31% say that either they themselves or their close relatives were victims of crime last year, but this is a decrease compared to 38% of last year and is also the lowest number since 1995.
More massive economic performance is reflected in increasing support for private business and market economy: around 71% of respondents across the area say that private business is necessary for development, this percentage has increased from 56% of 2007 (see Chart 6).
About 58% agree that the market economy is the only system that will allow their country to develop, this percentage has increased from 47% from last year.
Interestingly, 62% of respondents in Venezuela have the same view (and 80% support private business), although their left-wing president Hugo Chávez expropriates many private companies.
Brazil is a country that has a leading position in the area, as 19% of respondents mentioned (as compared to 18% last year), followed by the United States (9%, no change compared to last year) and Venezuela (9%, compared to 11% last year)
