For a long time, six main elements - carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus, and sulphur - were considered essential for life.
However, scientists have found that bacteria discovered in Mono Lake, California, are able to continue to grow after being replaced by phosphorus for arsenic.
"It will start to amaze you as much as possible," said Ariel D. Anbar of Arizona State University, co-author of the report.
