It's not like that.
The discovery "shows that other planetary organisms may be able to use other elements that drive biochemistry and that the set of elements we consider 'standard' may not be so necessary for life," explained Charles Cockell, professor at the Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute, Open University, Milton Keynes, United Kingdom.
Cockell wasn't part of the research team.
"This work is unusual because it shows the replacement of one element to another in the basic biochemistry and biochemical structure," Cockell added.
It wasn't a random find.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of the Astrobiological Institute at NASA, who conducted the study, focused on Mono Lake because it showed high arsenic levels.
The arsenic and phosphorus are chemically very similar elements, so it considered that the microbe, which is exposed to both elements, could be able to replace one after another.
"Arzen is poisonous mainly because its chemical behavior is very similar to phosphorus."
"The result is that organisms can be very difficult to separate these elements from each other."
"However, arsenic is so different that it doesn't work like phosphorus. When it gets into the body, it starts working in biochemical processes," Anbar explained.
Scientists gather bacteria known as GFAJ-1 and expose them to an increasing concentration of arsenic that bacteria are able to adapt and grow.
Microbes grow better in the action of phosphorus, but given that they can also survive with arsenic replacement, the possibility that the form of life that uses arsenic can occur naturally, either elsewhere on Earth or on another planet or moon, where arsenic is more common.
Jamie S. Foster, an assistant professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, said that the idea of arsenic, which could be replaced by phosphorus, was not new, but there was never an example on which this fact could be proved.
Arzen was more common in earlier times on Earth, she said, so scientists speculated that it could be used by earlier life forms.
"This suggests that there could have been other ways to create life, not just the way it was created in the early Earth," Foster said, which was not part of the Wolfe-Simon research team.
