In this way, both players will meet the prescribed penalty in the next match against Auxerre - with Real Madrid ending up in their group leading - and will be able to, de-carded, continue to the next stage.
Finally, the UEFA Disciplinary Board gave coach José Mourinh a two-game sentence and the guilty players received a cash penalty.
Provoking a yellow card under similar conditions is no new practice, but is more or less common in football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos of football, rules that are unwritten, but are being watched.
Part of the discussion in this case was due to the fact that its participant was the team Real Madrid (which boasts in its anthem of generosity and honor, and which has already fined its players for similar actions), and apparently also due to the drama led by Mourinh, who thus adds another episode to his long history of comedy and provocateur.
in any case, the debate revolves around whether this type of action, which is not expressly prohibited by the rules, is contrary to the principles of sport, i.e. whether there is circumvention in these acts; indeed, it is an action that respects the sports rules, whose meaning seems to be trying to circumvent.
It is discussed what type of damage such actions cause to the spirit of sport.
One of the essentials of sports behavior is the physical integrity of the opponents, which has not been violated in these cases, or there has been no violent game.
Another of these features characterizing a clean game is to avoid players having an advantage over the opponent team because of their offense - which did not happen here either.
Thus, paradoxical to the action of Real Madrid players is the fact that what we normally characterize as a ruse or circumventing the law has not been a hidden violation of the rules in order to avoid sanctions, but this behaviour should have been as evident as possible with the aim of obtaining the penalty.
They waited, and they like to get punished.
The next question, however, is what advantage the culprits will have from their deliberate transgression.
It must be noted here that the opponent is not in a disadvantaged position and that he will not get any benefit in the current match, as the obvious consequence is that the team itself will have fewer players.
And it's not even a useful strategy for the next game, because the club won't be able to count on these players.
Obviously, the advantage is that players will begin the next phase of the Champions League without cards, which could jeopardize their participation in the future match.
However, this is an advantage from the long-term perspective and with some degree of uncertainty, i.e. at first glance the team can be eliminated, and beyond that, the players will be punished, and they will go to the second round of cards, in which one card less than the first round is enough to be excluded.
So as the wheels continue, it will not be quite clear whether this is an advantage.
In short, and well, these negotiations do not go against the spirit of sport, which includes making strategic decisions that will allow maximum benefit to be obtained under the rules.
in the case we are dealing with here, players were not intended to avoid being punished (which would be a clear case of circumvention), but rather to choose when to submit to it.
They made a strategic decision without avoiding or fleeing punishment.
Although the line between wit and bypassing the rules is not very clear, I believe that in this case it was clearly a wit.
It seems to me that the controversy arises for two reasons: because it was two self-excretion and the way in which the transfer of instructions was carried out to provoke them away from the lead.
The damage to sports principles by these events is not as ethical as aesthetic.
