The United States amends the rules for issuing visas
People will have to turn to the Centres of the Services for Visa Applicants before interviewing the Consul Unit; the costs will be lower and the waiting time will be reduced.
As of 10 January 2011, the visa process will be changed at the United States Embassy and consulates.
With the new procedure, most applicants will have to contact the Centres for Visa Applicants (shortly from ASC English) before interviewing the Conservative Department.
The staff from the ASC will collect biometric information from the applicant and they will be evaluated by the Consular Department before the interview.
The new procedure will have certain advantages, including the following:
The total cost of handling the visa will be lower, no longer necessary to pay the fee for the appointment, the second for the processing of the application and other for the delivery of the document by the transport service.
The applicant shall pay only one fee covering all three services.
The current tariff will remain unchanged: the amount corresponding to $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visa cases (including temporary workers visas) and $390 for a visa for traders and investors.
People who wish to renew their visa will not have to go through an interview with a consular officer, but will only contact the nearest ASC, where they will submit their documents and will be fingerprinted.
Given that biometric information will be collected in the ASC, applicants who will require a second interview with the Conservative Department will spend less time here than in the past.
Likewise, those who will apply for a visa at consulates in Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay an extra charge for the service of $26.
For further information on the new visa application procedure, please visit the following website http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
