World lighting recovery plan
Yesterday, in Cancún, the United Nations proposed a plan to restore domestic lighting, business lighting and industrial space in 100 countries to achieve a greenhouse effect reduction (GES), which corresponds to almost one third of the additional constraints that need to be achieved in order to stabilise the planet's climate from now to 2020.
This ambitious plan is at the stage of major concrete projects that the UN intends to push through in Cancún to compensate for the absence of difficult-to-use commitments to reduce on the part of industrialised countries.
According to the plan presented yesterday, if we replace heated bulbs that monopolize 50 to 70% of the market with fluocompact bulbs or, even better, light bulbs with electroluminescent diodes (DEL or "LED" in English), a significant amount of 1.8 billion tonnes (Gt) of GES emissions on the planet due to lighting would be degraded.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of world emissions.
It's equivalent to 70% of the emissions from the car park across the planet.
In Copenhagen last year, large countries with a significant share in emissions such as the United States, China, Europe and others, among them Canada, joined voluntary reduction plans that should allow global GES emissions to fall from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
But we will need to subtract 5 Gt from this balance to achieve climate warming stabilization to 2 degrees Celsius by 2020 in order to exclude it from being out of control.
In heated filament lamps 95% of the energy is dispersed in the form of heat and the rest, i.e. 5%, is the light product.
With fluocompact bulbs, energy consumption is reduced by 75% and with new DEL bulbs, we reduce this consumption twice more.
Fluocompact bulbs can last from 6000 to 10,000 hours on average.
The new DEL light bulbs, which Philips introduced this week - this company reportedly participated in a UN study - have an estimated lifetime of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than a hot bulb, giving us an idea of possible savings with a compensation plan that would be applied in 100 countries.
All these new bulbs can also work with rheostats and radiate less heat.
And they don't contain any mercury.
Several experts have expressed reservations about fluocompact bulbs because they contain mercury and need to be sorted as hazardous waste, which is still not possible in developing countries, except that manufacturers would set up collections.
However, as the report states, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not a fluo-compact light bulb, but rather a thermal coal power plant that emits much mercury needed to produce electricity wasted in hot bulbs.
In the United States alone, these hubs put 25,000 tons of mercury into circulation each year.
The report also details the profits that each country would make from this international programme.
