Climate: how France hacked its funding promises
A year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to try to keep promises for quickly unblocked funding (spoken funding with a fast start) or premature), implemented by developed countries.
And the great French hacks have been exposed
In the Copenhagen Agreement, developed countries undertook to provide $30 billion in 2010-2012.
The European Union has promised EUR 7.2 billion for three years and France EUR 1.26 billion (i.e. 420 million per year).
At the launch of COP16, the EU pulled a big ace to convince its partners of the reality of its commitment to financing fast start: a report specifying the action of its Member States, a press conference, a grand side event, the distribution of brochures...
Transparent operations invaluable and valued at their true value: advanced countries and civil society would like all developed countries and civil society to do them equally and with the same degree of precision.
The EU announces that it released EUR 2.2 billion in 2010, which brings it on the right track to keep its promise of 7.2 billion in 2012.
But if we focus on detail, we find that things are much more complicated.
These funds are "new and additional' under the Copenhagen Agreement to ensure that the increased burden is implemented without prejudice to Public Aid for Development.
Unfortunately, there is no consensus on what "new and additional" means.
While the European Commission has proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, have blocked the process.
Today, everyone chooses the reference that suits them best.
For example, the European Commission considered 2009 to be a reference: international funding has been preserved and it adds 150 million to it for three years of funding fast start.
Other countries have selected similar references with annual payment deadlines or with public aid deadlines for development.
By contrast, France considers that the financing of "all new projects' in 2010 is "new and additional'.
In other words, there is no reference to the expenditure of previous periods or to the global level of Public Aid for the Development of d'Aide publique au développement.
In particular, the overall amount of support from France towards developing countries may remain constant (or even decrease) to comply with its commitment to financing "new and additional'....
Another crucial element is the distribution of donations and loans.
There is no rule yet and everyone chooses their own method of calculation.
Some, such as France, consider that 1€ borrowed equals 1€ donated.
Clearly, it is hard to prove: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans can be documented for some investments that are profitable (often projects related to reducing emissions, consisting of more efficient technologies), it is foolish to present one euro that we receive as the equivalent of one euro that we give... , we should not understand it on the basis of our commitments but as the loan price for a creditor country (i.e. the interest rate equivalent).
But France can only give such a justification: it "respects" its commitment of EUR 420 million, making it 91.5 percent loan (EUR 389,8 million) and 8,5% donations (EUR 36.1 million) - see the EU document to verify it for yourself.
It is the only country of the Union using a loan on such a scale.
Germany requested 46% of this, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (including others) comply with their 100% donation obligations.
In other words, if the vast majority of the European Union gives € 1 in the course of its promise, France will only give 10 cents and consider this effort comparable.
Beautiful trickery!
For the sake of summary, when financing "fast start" France operates with double cheating: on the one hand, with the development of the share in time and on the other hand with a real financial burden.
Although it only issues EUR 36.1 million, it can convince it that it spends EUR 420 million "new and additional" in connection with its promises.
The manipulation of the Minister of Finance (because it seems that, although Bercy was the one who made such decisions) could have a double negative impact, at the same time within the EU (why would the Member States continue to donate when they just need to borrow?) and in negotiations, because developing countries are not completely naive...
The early funding chapter is just a small question, relatively short-term, in relation to a series of climate discussions.
But it could be a grain of sand in an enormous machine like the UNFCCC.
Let's hope it's not our case.
Whatever it is, it is necessary to draw knowledge from this first year of early funding.
First, France should announce a change in its way of keeping accounting records for 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of respect for its commitments and politeness and justice towards other countries of the European Union.
But, above all, France should avoid discussing deposits in long-term funding (another crucial chapter currently discussed): we will not escape the issue of 'additionality' or the way in which loans are booked.
France should change its position in order to become so progressive with these deposits as with others.
So everyone puts hope in the new Environment Minister, Mrs Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
The surprising announcement about France's fast start and its vision of "additionality" and the use of loans could lead to an increase in the level of international confidence necessary to move forward in discussions.
